      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Also called</span><span class="meta-value">Declared Data, Intentional Data</span></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Zero-party data</strong> is information that customers deliberately and proactively share with a brand — including their preferences, purchase intentions, personal context, and feedback. Unlike first-party data (passively collected from behaviour) or third-party data (bought from data brokers), zero-party data is explicitly given by the customer. It is the most accurate, consent-assured, and privacy-regulation-friendly data type available to marketers.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">General Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Also Called</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Declared Data, Intentional Data</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Read Time</div>
            <div class="tms-value">7 min</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">The term "zero-party data" was coined by Forrester Research analyst Fatemeh Khatibloo and has become central to marketing strategy discussions as the industry navigates the post-third-party-cookie world. The concept is simple: stop inferring what customers want from their behaviour — ask them directly.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is zero-party data?</h2>
        <p>Zero-party data is any information a customer consciously and willingly provides to a brand, with the clear understanding that the brand will use it to personalise their experience. The customer is the active participant in the data exchange, not the passive subject.</p>
        <p>The "zero" in zero-party refers to the fact that there is zero data brokerage or inference involved. The data comes directly from the source with full intent — the customer chose to provide it.</p>
        <p>Examples of zero-party data:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Answers to a product quiz ("What's your skin type?" on a skincare brand's website)</li>
          <li>Preference selections in an email subscription centre ("Send me emails about: SEO / content / social media")</li>
          <li>Onboarding survey answers ("What's your biggest marketing challenge?") in a SaaS product</li>
          <li>Wishlist additions and saved items where the customer explicitly tags preferences</li>
          <li>Profile information filled in voluntarily ("I manage a team of 10+", "I'm in B2B SaaS")</li>
          <li>Post-purchase survey responses ("What made you choose us?", "How would you rate the experience?")</li>
          <li>Community or forum profile data where customers self-describe their interests</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">The four data types ranked by trust and accuracy</div>
          <p><strong>Zero-party</strong> (customer-declared, highest trust) → <strong>First-party</strong> (brand-observed behaviour) → <strong>Second-party</strong> (partner-shared first-party data) → <strong>Third-party</strong> (data broker aggregations, lowest trust). Zero-party data is at the top because the customer consciously chose to share it.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-first-party">Zero-party data vs first-party data</h2>
        <p>The distinction between zero-party and first-party data is commonly misunderstood, but it matters for both privacy compliance and data quality.</p>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Factor</th><th>Zero-Party Data</th><th>First-Party Data</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>How collected</strong></td><td>Customer actively provides it</td><td>Brand observes customer behaviour</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Examples</strong></td><td>Quiz answers, preference settings, surveys</td><td>Purchase history, page views, email opens</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Accuracy</strong></td><td>Very high (declared intent)</td><td>Medium (inferred from behaviour)</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Privacy risk</strong></td><td>Very low</td><td>Low-medium (depends on tracking method)</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>GDPR basis</strong></td><td>Consent (most straightforward)</td><td>Legitimate interest or consent</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Requires inference?</strong></td><td>No</td><td>Often yes</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why zero-party data matters now</h2>
        <p>Three converging trends have made zero-party data a strategic priority for marketers in 2024-2026:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Third-party cookie deprecation.</strong> Safari and Firefox have blocked third-party cookies for years. Chrome's long-delayed phase-out programme, plus Google Privacy Sandbox, has pushed marketers to find alternative data sources. Zero-party data fills the gap without requiring inferred behavioural tracking.</li>
          <li><strong>GDPR, CCPA, and global privacy regulation tightening.</strong> Regulators are scrutinising inferred data collection more aggressively. Zero-party data collected through explicit consent is the cleanest legal foundation for personalisation programmes.</li>
          <li><strong>Customer preference for transparency.</strong> Research consistently shows that customers are more willing to share data when they understand how it will be used to benefit them. A clear value exchange — "tell us your preferences, get more relevant content" — outperforms invisible tracking in building trust.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="collection-methods">Best zero-party data collection methods</h2>
        <p>The most effective zero-party data collection methods make the value exchange explicit and immediate:</p>

        <h3>Quizzes and assessments</h3>
        <p>Product recommendation quizzes are the highest-converting zero-party data collection format in e-commerce. A "Find your perfect X" quiz collects 5-10 preference signals while delivering immediate personalised value (the recommendation). Conversion rates on quiz-to-purchase flows typically run 2-3x higher than standard product pages.</p>

        <h3>Preference centres</h3>
        <p>Email preference centres where subscribers can choose their content interests, email frequency, and format (digest vs individual sends) collect valuable segmentation data while reducing unsubscribe rates. Subscribers who set preferences are more engaged than those who didn't.</p>

        <h3>Onboarding flows</h3>
        <p>SaaS products that ask "What's your role?", "What's your team size?", and "What's your primary goal?" during onboarding collect zero-party data that enables personalised product tours, relevant in-app content, and smarter email nurture sequences.</p>

        <h3>Post-purchase surveys</h3>
        <p>A two-question post-purchase survey ("How did you hear about us?" + "What made you buy?") provides both attribution data and purchase intent context. The conversion moment is the highest-trust moment for asking customers questions.</p>

        <h3>Community profiles and forum participation</h3>
        <p>In branded communities or online forums, customers self-describe their interests, expertise levels, and challenges. This voluntary self-description is rich zero-party data for segmentation and personalisation.</p>

        <h2 id="using-zero-party-data">How to use zero-party data in marketing</h2>
        <p>Collecting zero-party data creates obligation: you must actually use it to improve the customer experience, or the trust invested in sharing it is eroded.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Email segmentation.</strong> Use declared interests to send relevant content. A subscriber who said "I'm interested in local SEO" should receive local SEO content, not generic marketing updates.</li>
          <li><strong>Product recommendations.</strong> Skincare quiz answers should directly determine which products appear in the post-quiz recommendation and in retargeting emails.</li>
          <li><strong>Personalised onboarding.</strong> SaaS onboarding paths should branch based on the role, use case, and goal declared during signup.</li>
          <li><strong>Ad audience exclusions and targeting.</strong> Use declared purchase intent ("I'm planning to buy in the next 30 days") to prioritise ad spend on high-intent segments.</li>
          <li><strong>Content personalisation.</strong> Dynamic website content, chatbot conversation routing, and homepage messaging can all be personalised based on zero-party data collected from previous visits.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="best-practices">Best practices for zero-party data</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Make the value exchange explicit and immediate.</strong> Tell customers why you're asking and what they'll get. "Answer 3 questions to get a personalised recommendation" is more compelling than "Help us serve you better."</li>
          <li><strong>Keep questions short.</strong> More than 5 questions in a quiz or onboarding flow reduces completion rates significantly. Ask only what you'll actually use.</li>
          <li><strong>Give customers control over their data.</strong> Provide a preference centre where customers can update, extend, or delete their declared data at any time. This is both a legal requirement and a trust signal.</li>
          <li><strong>Use the data visibly.</strong> When a customer sees their preferences reflected in the content or recommendations they receive, it reinforces the value of sharing. Invisible personalisation reduces future sharing willingness.</li>
          <li><strong>Refresh data regularly.</strong> Preferences change. A customer's declared interests from 18 months ago may no longer reflect current needs. Build re-engagement flows that invite customers to update their preferences.</li>
          <li><strong>Layer zero-party with first-party data.</strong> Declared preferences combined with observed behaviour are more powerful than either alone. A customer who declared "I'm interested in SEO" and also clicked every SEO email is a higher-value segment than one who only declared the interest.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — collecting data without using it</div>
          <p>Many brands run preference surveys or quizzes but fail to integrate the responses into their CRM or email platform. Customers who share preferences and then receive generic, non-personalised communications quickly disengage. The data collection must be wired into your personalisation stack before you start collecting.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What is the difference between zero-party data and first-party data?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>First-party data is behavioural data passively collected by a brand as customers interact with their website, app, or emails (purchase history, page views, clicks). Zero-party data is actively shared by the customer through quizzes, preference centres, surveys, or profile settings. Zero-party data requires explicit sharing; first-party data is inferred from behaviour.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Why is zero-party data important in a cookieless world?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>As third-party cookies phase out and browser tracking becomes restricted, marketers lose access to behavioural data collected across the web. Zero-party data fills this gap by going directly to the source — asking customers what they want. It's privacy-compliant by design because customers choose to share it.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What are examples of zero-party data?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Common zero-party data examples include: product preference selections in an onboarding quiz, answers to "What brings you here today?" on a website popup, email frequency preferences set in a subscription centre, purchase intent signals from a wishlist, and feedback from post-purchase surveys.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Is zero-party data GDPR-compliant?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes, when collected correctly. Because zero-party data is explicitly shared by the customer, it fulfils GDPR's consent requirement. Brands must still inform customers how the data will be used, provide the ability to update or delete it, and not use it beyond the stated purpose.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How do you encourage customers to share zero-party data?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>The best incentive is demonstrable value: customers share preferences when they trust the brand will use them to improve their experience. Personalised product recommendations, relevant content, and less irrelevant marketing are the value exchange. Quizzes with instant results, preference centres, and onboarding flows all perform well for zero-party data collection.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

